conflict, the regional and international implications of such conflicts, and what the international community can do to minimize the potential for instability and violence. Drawn from recent issues of Survival, they are organized along thematic rather than regional lines, and will be required reading for scholars, students, and policymakers alike. The contributors to the volume include Michael Brown on the causes and implications of ethnic conflict, Anthony Smith on the ethnic sources of nationalism, David Welsh on domestic politics and ethnic conflict, Renée de Nevers on democratization and ethnic conflict, and Pierre Hassner on nationalism and internationalism. Jack Snyder writes on nationalism and the crisis of the post-Soviet state, Barry Posen on the security dilemma and ethnic conflict, Kathleen Newland on ethnic conflict and refugees, Jenonne Walker on international mediation of ethnic conflicts, and Robert Cooper and Mats Berdal on outside intervention in ethnic conflicts, Adam Roberts discusses the U.N. and international security, and John Chipman explores managing the politics of parochialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConflict management. 0aEthnic conflict. 0aMediation, International. 0aSecurity, International. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Michael E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Michael E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChipman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassner, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevers, Renée de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewland, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPosen, Barry R.,